My understanding is the table to be caculated first decides the order of the caculation, ie. if the first table to be caculated is an outer table, we'll caculate ALL the outer tables then the inner tables and if the first table to be caculated is an inner table, we'll caculate this inner table and then outer tables if we meet one.

On the other hand, if displayNothing doesnt exist, the first table to be caculated will be an inner table where varGrandTotal would be assigned a vaule. That explains that you could get the expected result when calling displayGrandTotal().

bug.short_desc: [security] Platform level TrustManager

long_desc.thetext:
Version: 3.3.0 Build id: I20061102-1715
To better support SSL connections to servers with self signed or otherwise invalid certificates, it would be nice if there were a global TrustManager available for plugins to use. This trust manager should be an extension to the built in Java Trust manager and should allow new certificates to be added programatically. The certificates should be stored in an encrypted keystore in a similar way to the current Eclipse keyring.
The set of trusted certificates will be the union of those provided by the default java trust manager (cacerts file of for Sun) and the certificates that have been accepted by this trust manager (and saved into a local KeyStore)
Once there is a custom TrustManager available, UI code can be added to the platform to prompt the user to accept new certificates. These certificates can either be accepted temporarily for the current session or permanently.
moving to the Equinox Incubator where the security work is happening
Brock, would you have some time available to prototype such a thing?

I do have a prototype, but it requires the TrustManager interface which doesn't appear to be part of the CDC 1.0/Foundation 1.0 environment. Would it be possible to bundle it as an optional service or something?
Also, how much of a prototype do you need? So far i have a trust manager that delegates to the default one and can store extra certificates, but haven't implemented a callback to prompt the user.

(In reply to comment #3) > I do have a prototype, but it requires the TrustManager interface which doesn't > appear to be part of the CDC 1.0/Foundation 1.0 environment. Would it be > possible to bundle it as an optional service or something?
If the platform trust manager can be in a "normal" bundle then it should not be a problem to require a higher Execution Environment. If the trust manager needs to be available to the framework implementation then it would be great if it could be delivered as a framework extension that used the framework adaptor hooks see http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/Adaptor_Hooks
We have been doing other work WRT signed bundles to delegate trust authority out from the framework. See CertificateTrustAuthority in the org.eclipse.osgi.internal.provisional.verifier package (in the org.eclipse.osgi bundle). Other bundles are allowed to implement this service interface to provide their own trust authority. Currently the framework implements a trust authority that uses the standard java cacerts.

bug.short_desc: C/C++ Project browser not updated after refactoring.

long_desc.thetext:
This problem is when you have the .h and .cpp of a class in C/C++ Projects View are expanded, when you rename the class from the editor the elements are not renamed in the C/C++ Projects view. Even if you do a refresh or collapse and expand the .h and .cpp files in the C/C++ Project View.
If you rename the class in the editor and the .h and .cpp are not expanded (that is class is not listed) in the C/C++ Project View, when you expand the .h and .cpp in browser, they are update with the correct name.
We're going to take a look at this for 3.1.2

I've verified that this is definitely a race condition. Sometimes the C/C++ Projects view gets refreshed before the underlying model is updated.
For example, if I rename ClassA to ClassB (via refactoring), sometimes, it will still show up as ClassA in the view, because the view is updated before the model. If I rename ClassB to ClassC, it will show up as ClassB, because the view is updated with the old model instead of the new one.
I haven't determined yet if this is genuinely a threading issue, or whether jobs are being posted to the display thread in the wrong order. I'll keep you posted.
Hmm, I thought only model updates kicked off the view update, i.e. C element changes. I could be wrong, though.

Yes, model updates still kick off view updates, which is why this has left me so puzzled. It looks like it's a caching issue involving shared WorkingCopies. I can reliably prevent this bug from happening within BaseCElementContentProvider.getChildren().
On line 194, getChildren() calls ITranslationUnit.findSharedWorkingCopy(). This method sometimes returns a stale WorkingCopy which contains the code prior to refactoring. It then calls getTranslationUnitChildren() on the stale WorkingCopy.
If I change this to always fetch the CModel from the TranslationUnit, instead of the shared WorkingCopy, the view is updated properly.
I'll poke around the shared WorkingCopy cache to see why it sometimes gives back a stale copy.
I think you got it. I have always been worried about the shared working copy thing. I'm sure there's some multi-threading bugs there. Thanks, Jay!
I have seen race condition before, see the bug 154056. https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=154056 You may be running into the same.

Created an attachment (id=57297) Proposed patch
It turns out that refactoring doesn't use the same shared WorkingCopy as the rest of CDT because refactoring provides its own IBufferFactory. The shared WorkingCopy cache differentiates between WorkingCopies from different IBufferFactories.
The BaseCElementProvider, which populates the CView and the outline, only finds shared WorkingCopies that originate from CDT. So changes done by refactoring is not visible to this part of the logic until the changes have been reconciled by the MonoReconciler threads.
The MonoReconciler threads get into a race condition with the UI thread when the CView is being refreshed because they are both working off the shared WorkingCopies.
We can avoid this problem completely by updating the CView using TranslationUnits (which is guaranteed to contain the refactoring changes) instead of the shared WorkingCopies. The attached patch implements this change.
Since the CView is only updated when resource changes are committed, we don't need to populate it using WorkingCopies.

Note that this would be in contrast to current 4.0, where changes have been applied to make the CView consistently show the working copy content. See bug 147694 comment 5 and following. BTW, I don't think this issue is specific to refactoring. The cview simply ignores working copy deltas, ie. any modification to a working copy (e.g. editing) will make the CView inconsistent.
Thanks for the pointer, Toni. Should we keep the current behaviour for 3.1.2 (potentially less confusing for existing 3.1.x users), or change it so that the outline and the CView are in sync?

Created an attachment (id=57342) Patch for 147694 backported for cdt_3_1
I hunted down Markus' changes for 147694, which maintain consistency between the CView and WorkingCopies. I've backported it for cdt_3_1 and attached it here.
So my initial patch keeps the CView in sync with what's on disk (CDT pre-4.0 behaviour). The second patch keeps the CView in sync with WorkingCopies (CDT 4.0 behaviour)

bug.short_desc: Unnecessary locking in ResourceChangeUpdaterProvider

long_desc.thetext: This defect is opened as a follow up to bug 164637. The class ResourceChangeUpdateProvider is responsible of: (1) processing resource change events (2) updating the Test Navigator content The problem is that (1) must be performed while the event is being dispatched (because the event information gets discarded as soon resourceChanged() returns), and that (2) must be performed in the UI thread. The current answer to these constraints is to perform (1) and (2) in a runnable invoked in a Display.getDefault().syncExec() call. Using asyncExec() invalidates constraint (1) and not using a xsyncExec() invalidates (2). There should be a finer-grained answer to this problem, consisting in processing the event while it is dispatched, and scheduling the navigator's refresh in an asyncExec(), thus reducing the resource change's thread locking to zero.

bug.short_desc: add conditional compilation support to DOM AST and Index

long_desc.thetext:
Currently the parser throws away anything it finds in compilation path that is not in the current compilation context (i.e. currently enabled based upon the currently defined macros). As a result you don't get an AST or any info in the index for anything contained in that path.
I propose that we add new node types to the AST and Index to support this.
Off the top of my head, this would require supporting:
#if #elif #else #ifdef #ifndef
Chris, is this something you're looking to see present in CDT 4.0?

(In reply to comment #1) > Chris, is this something you're looking to see present in CDT 4.0?
We were hoping to do this, yes. It's on the lower end of our list of priorties though so we've only just started on it.
Looks like this is going to drop off the list for 4.0
Future means you commit to fix it in the Future. Inboxes can't make committments. Moving to '--'.

I see Emmanuel added himself to the cc: list so I thought I should update this bug as to our thoughts...
We thought long and hard about the problem about 6 months ago. It is a really difficult problem to solve. When I originally filed this bug I was thinking that we could just place preprocessor nodes in the tree and evaluate them when the tree is traversed later.
The problem with the preprocessor though is that conditional compilation statements can literally appear anywhere in the code, and do not have to be on the bounds of well formed expressions and statements, or even on the bounds well formed productions of the C/C++ grammar. Throw in macros that use other macros and it gets even messier. As such, the two branches of the AST that would follow a conditional node could be wildly different.
An example (a bit contrived):
#ifdef SOMETHING int #else MyClass #endif y;
In this case, you don't know what the type of y is until compile time. You can similarly construct contrived examples that are say, a declaration versus a statement, or pretty much any arbitrary combination of legal constructs. It gets particularly interesting/difficult when you have conditionally defined macros that evaluate to different, large blocks of text.
What this means is that each subtree rooted at the preprocessor node might need to contain arbitrary amounts of the remaining program in order to provide a correct tree in the context of the macros that are defined.
There is a paper by Alejandra Garrido and Ralph Johnston called "Challenges of Refactoring C Programs" that goes into some of these issues. They have interesting ideas about refactoring the incomplete statements in the conditional compilation blocks so that these statements are complete. An interesting thought, but I think in most cases the users will object to having to refactor their code to enable other refactorings.
Anyway, I forsee a lot of thought and discussion needing to go into this before anything can be done. Really this should be the subject of someone's PhD thesis :-P
It is probably more practical in the short term to just allow the user to specify a working set of configurations (i.e. include paths and #defines) for which they want AST and index based operations to apply. For each configuration, parse the code and build up a separate index. Then things like search and refactoring can be applied to each configuration separately. It means that things get much slower the more configurations you have, but at least you can be sure that the analysis is complete.

> anything can be done. Really this should be the subject of someone's PhD > thesis :-P
And this was the topic of Ale's thesis. I'm not sure I ever got a copy of her thesis in the end (but we do know her supervisor :). I wonder if it changed from the papers she wrote.
I thought her idea was to handle everything in the AST, i.e. duplicate nodes where necessary to keep things simple, not to refactor the actual source. At least that's what I understood.

Thanks for your update Chris. I tried this during my diploma thesis and came to the same result its a difficult problem to solve. I don't know the paper you mentioned but I have a copy of Alejandra's dissertation. As far as I remember her solution was to manipulate the internal model of the source code so that the conditional directives appears only between complete syntactical constructs like statements or declarations. Your solution with several configuration would be easier and faster to implement.
